raw_data.title: Cloud Analyst I
raw_data.description: The Cloud Analyst monitors, analyzes, and optimizes cloud infrastructure to ensure efficiency, security, and compliance with federal standards like FedRAMP and NIST. They assess cloud performance, troubleshoot issues, and recommend improvements to enhance scalability and cost-effectiveness. This role involves managing cloud resources, tracking usage metrics, and identifying potential risks or inefficiencies. The analyst collaborates with IT teams to implement best practices in cloud security, automation, and governance. Strong expertise in AWS, Azure, or Google Cloud, along with monitoring tools like CloudWatch, Azure Monitor, or Splunk, is essential. They also support cloud migrations, conduct reporting, and provide insights to drive data-driven decision-making.

This role involves conducting in-depth assessments, identifying risks, and implementing automation to streamline cloud operations. The analyst collaborates with cross-functional teams to support cloud migrations, optimize workloads, and enforce governance best practices. Expertise in AWS, Azure, or Google Cloud, along with tools like CloudWatch, Azure Monitor, Splunk, and Terraform, is essential. They also mentor junior analysts, produce technical reports, and provide strategic insights to support cloud initiatives.

raw_data.title: Cloud Architect I
raw_data.description: A Cloud Architect is responsible for designing, implementing, and managing cloud infrastructure to meet the specific needs of an organization. They ensure cloud solutions are scalable, secure, and cost-effective, optimizing performance and supporting business goals. The role involves evaluating existing IT systems, selecting appropriate cloud platforms (e.g., AWS, Azure, GCP), and integrating cloud services with on-premise solutions. They collaborate with cross-functional teams to implement cloud strategies, oversee migrations, and establish disaster recovery plans. A successful Cloud Architect also ensures compliance with security standards and manages cloud resources efficiently. Best practices include continuous learning, automated deployment, and robust monitoring to ensure high availability and cost control.

raw_data.title: Cloud Architect II

They develop cloud architectures that align with organizational goals, ensuring compliance with federal standards like FedRAMP, NIST, and FISMA. This role involves evaluating emerging technologies, enhancing cloud security, and driving automation to improve efficiency. The architect collaborates with cross-functional teams to integrate cloud-native services, optimize costs, and enhance performance. Expertise in AWS, Azure, or Google Cloud, along with infrastructure as code (IaC) tools like Terraform or CloudFormation, is essential. They also provide technical leadership, troubleshoot complex cloud issues, and mentor junior engineers.

They work with cloud platforms such as AWS, Azure, or Google Cloud to build scalable and efficient solutions. This entry-level role requires proficiency in programming languages like Python, Java, or JavaScript and knowledge of cloud-native technologies like containers and serverless architecture. The Cloud Developer I collaborates with senior developers and cloud architects to implement features, troubleshoot issues, and ensure performance optimization. They also participate in code reviews, testing, and documentation to ensure quality and maintainability. Best practices include following Agile methodologies, leveraging cloud automation tools, and maintaining secure coding standards.

raw_data.title: Cloud Developer II
raw_data.description: A Cloud Developer II is responsible for designing, developing, and deploying more complex cloud-based applications and services. They possess advanced knowledge of cloud platforms (AWS, Azure, or Google Cloud) and work with technologies like microservices, containers, and serverless architectures. This role requires strong programming skills in languages such as Python, Java, or Node.js, along with experience in database management and cloud security practices. The Cloud Developer II collaborates with cross-functional teams, including Cloud Architects and DevOps Engineers, to implement and optimize cloud solutions. They lead code reviews, mentor junior developers, and ensure the scalability, security, and performance of cloud-based systems. Best practices include embracing automation, continuous integration/continuous deployment (CI/CD) pipelines, and adhering to agile development processes.

raw_data.title: Cloud Developer III
raw_data.description: A Cloud Developer III is responsible for leading the design, development, and optimization of complex cloud-based applications and services. With advanced expertise in cloud platforms (AWS, Azure, or Google Cloud), they leverage cutting-edge technologies like container orchestration, Kubernetes, and serverless computing to create highly scalable, secure, and performant solutions. This senior-level role requires deep knowledge of cloud architecture, distributed systems, and best practices in DevOps, security, and cost management. The Cloud Developer III works closely with Cloud Architects, DevOps teams, and other stakeholders to drive technical decision-making, mentor junior developers, and ensure the reliability and efficiency of cloud systems. They are also responsible for troubleshooting complex issues, automating processes, and leading the implementation of CI/CD pipelines. Best practices include advocating for high-quality code standards, fostering innovation, and optimizing cloud resource usage for cost efficiency.

raw_data.title: Cloud DevSecOps Engineer
raw_data.description: The Cloud DevSecOps Engineer integrates security into cloud development and operations, ensuring compliance with FedRAMP, NIST, and zero-trust architectures. They design and implement secure CI/CD pipelines, automate security controls, and monitor cloud environments for vulnerabilities. This role involves collaborating with development, security, and operations teams to enforce best practices in cloud security, compliance, and infrastructure as code (IaC). The engineer leverages tools like Terraform, Ansible, Kubernetes, and security platforms such as AWS Security Hub, Azure Security Center, or Prisma Cloud. They also conduct security assessments, incident response, and continuous monitoring to enhance cloud resilience. Strong expertise in AWS, Azure, or Google Cloud, along with DevSecOps methodologies, is essential.

raw_data.title: Cloud Engineer I
raw_data.description: The Cloud Engineer I assists in designing, deploying, and maintaining cloud-based solutions, ensuring efficiency and security in alignment with organizational requirements. They support cloud migrations, troubleshoot basic issues, and optimize performance under the guidance of senior engineers. This role involves working with cloud platforms such as AWS, Azure, or Google Cloud and utilizing automation tools like Terraform or CloudFormation. The engineer helps implement best practices in cloud security, scalability, and cost optimization. They collaborate with IT teams to monitor cloud resources, apply updates, and ensure compliance with industry standards. Strong foundational knowledge of networking, scripting, and cloud services is essential for success in this role.

raw_data.title: Cloud Engineer II
raw_data.description: The Cloud Engineer II designs, deploys, and optimizes cloud infrastructure to ensure scalability, security, and compliance with federal standards like FedRAMP and NIST. They implement automation, manage cloud resources, and support migrations to AWS, Azure, or Google Cloud. This role involves troubleshooting complex issues, improving performance, and integrating infrastructure-as-code (IaC) tools such as Terraform or CloudFormation. The engineer collaborates with security, development, and operations teams to enhance cloud resilience and enforce best practices. Expertise in networking, identity management, and containerized workloads (Docker, Kubernetes) is essential. They also contribute to cost optimization, monitoring, and documentation to support cloud operations.

raw_data.title: Cloud Platform Engineer I
raw_data.description: A Cloud Platform Engineer I is responsible for assisting in the design, implementation, and maintenance of cloud infrastructure and platforms. This entry-level role involves working with cloud providers like AWS, Azure, or Google Cloud to deploy and manage cloud services, ensuring they are scalable, reliable, and secure. The Cloud Platform Engineer I supports automation efforts, monitors cloud resources, and assists with troubleshooting and optimizing cloud environments. They work closely with senior engineers and architects to learn best practices in cloud management, infrastructure-as-code (IaC), and cloud security. Key responsibilities also include participating in performance monitoring, cost optimization, and supporting disaster recovery efforts. Best practices include leveraging cloud-native tools, automation, and ensuring alignment with security and compliance standards.

raw_data.title: Cloud Platform Engineer II
raw_data.description: A Cloud Platform Engineer III is responsible for leading the design, deployment, and management of complex cloud infrastructure solutions, ensuring they meet high standards for scalability, performance, and security. This senior-level role involves working with cloud platforms such as AWS, Azure, or Google Cloud, and leveraging tools for automation, infrastructure-as-code (IaC), and container orchestration (e.g., Kubernetes). The Cloud Platform Engineer III plays a key role in optimizing cloud environments, troubleshooting performance issues, managing high-availability configurations, and implementing disaster recovery plans. They also collaborate with cross-functional teams, mentor junior engineers, and lead initiatives to improve cloud operations. Best practices include driving automation, enhancing cloud security, ensuring cost efficiency, and advocating for continuous monitoring and performance optimization of cloud infrastructure.

raw_data.title: Cloud Product Manager
raw_data.description: The Cloud Product Manager oversees the development, strategy, and lifecycle of cloud-based products, ensuring they align with business and government requirements. They collaborate with engineering, security, and operations teams to define product roadmaps, optimize performance, and ensure compliance with FedRAMP, NIST, and other federal standards. This role involves gathering stakeholder requirements, prioritizing features, and driving innovation to enhance cloud offerings. The Product Manager leverages market research and user feedback to refine cloud services, improve adoption, and manage costs effectively. Strong expertise in cloud platforms like AWS, Azure, or Google Cloud, along with Agile methodologies, is essential. They also coordinate with vendors, ensure seamless integration, and support go-to-market strategies.

raw_data.title: Cloud Program Manager I
raw_data.description: A Cloud Program Manager I is responsible for coordinating and overseeing multiple cloud projects within an organization, ensuring alignment with strategic goals and successful delivery. This entry-level program management role involves managing timelines, resources, and risks across various cloud initiatives. They work closely with project managers, cloud architects, and development teams to ensure that cloud projects are executed efficiently and meet quality standards. The Cloud Program Manager I is also involved in tracking progress, providing status reports, and maintaining communication with stakeholders. Key responsibilities include ensuring adherence to best practices, facilitating program governance, and supporting continuous improvement. Best practices include fostering collaboration, maintaining clear communication channels, and ensuring that cloud solutions are cost-effective, secure, and scalable.

raw_data.title: Cloud Program Manager II
raw_data.description: A Cloud Program Manager II is responsible for overseeing and managing multiple cloud-related programs, ensuring they align with business objectives, timelines, and budgets. This mid-level role involves coordinating cross-functional teams, including cloud architects, developers, and project managers, to execute complex cloud initiatives. The Cloud Program Manager II defines program scope, sets strategic goals, manages risks, and ensures that each project delivers cloud solutions that are secure, scalable, and cost-effective. They track program performance, generate progress reports, and communicate with senior leadership and stakeholders. Additionally, they mentor junior program managers and drive continuous improvement in program delivery. Best practices include ensuring strong stakeholder management, maintaining clear governance structures, and prioritizing cloud security, compliance, and performance in all program activities.

raw_data.title: Cloud Project Manager
raw_data.description: A Cloud Project Manager oversees the planning, execution, and delivery of cloud-based projects, ensuring they align with business goals, timelines, and budgets. They manage cross-functional teams, including developers, architects, and stakeholders, to ensure effective collaboration and communication throughout the project lifecycle. The role requires expertise in cloud technologies, project management methodologies (e.g., Agile, Scrum), and strong organizational skills. The Cloud Project Manager defines project scope, sets milestones, monitors progress, mitigates risks, and ensures that cloud solutions meet security, compliance, and performance standards. They also manage vendor relationships and are responsible for resource allocation, budget tracking, and reporting. Best practices include clear documentation, proactive issue resolution, and ensuring that cloud implementations are scalable, secure, and cost-effective.

raw_data.title: Cloud Security SME
raw_data.description: The Cloud Security SME provides expert guidance on securing cloud environments, ensuring compliance with federal regulations such as FedRAMP, NIST, and FISMA. They assess cloud architectures, identify security risks, and implement best practices to protect data, applications, and infrastructure. This role involves developing security policies, automating compliance controls, and advising stakeholders on risk mitigation strategies. The SME collaborates with engineering and operations teams to integrate identity management, encryption, and zero-trust security models. Expertise in AWS, Azure, or Google Cloud security services, along with tools like SIEM, IAM, and CSPM, is essential. They also conduct security assessments, incident response planning, and training to strengthen cloud security posture.

raw_data.title: Cloud Software Engineer I
raw_data.description: A Cloud Software Engineer I is responsible for developing, testing, and maintaining cloud-based software applications and services. This entry-level role requires proficiency in programming languages like Python, Java, or JavaScript and an understanding of cloud platforms such as AWS, Azure, or Google Cloud. The Cloud Software Engineer I collaborates with senior engineers to implement cloud solutions, integrate APIs, and troubleshoot issues related to cloud systems. They are also involved in writing clean, efficient, and scalable code, conducting unit testing, and contributing to software documentation. Best practices include following Agile methodologies, using version control systems (e.g., Git), and adhering to cloud security standards to ensure safe and reliable application deployment.

raw_data.title: Cloud Software Engineer II
raw_data.description: A Cloud Software Engineer II is responsible for designing, developing, and optimizing cloud-based software applications and services with a focus on scalability, performance, and security. This mid-level role requires proficiency in cloud platforms such as AWS, Azure, or Google Cloud, along with expertise in programming languages like Python, Java, or Node.js. The Cloud Software Engineer II collaborates with cross-functional teams, including Cloud Architects and DevOps engineers, to integrate cloud services, build APIs, and ensure that cloud solutions meet business needs. They are also involved in code reviews, mentoring junior engineers, and ensuring adherence to best practices in software development, security, and cloud infrastructure. Best practices include using CI/CD pipelines, optimizing cloud resources for cost efficiency, and maintaining high code quality standards.

raw_data.title: Cloud Software Engineer III

This senior-level role requires deep expertise in cloud platforms such as AWS, Azure, or Google Cloud, and proficiency in multiple programming languages like Python, Java, or Go. The Cloud Software Engineer III takes ownership of end-to-end cloud application development, ensuring scalability, security, and high performance. They work closely with Cloud Architects, DevOps, and cross-functional teams to implement complex cloud solutions, manage integrations, and troubleshoot critical issues. They also mentor junior engineers, conduct code reviews, and enforce best practices in software development, cloud security, and infrastructure management. Best practices include leveraging automation, continuous integration, cost optimization strategies, and ensuring the alignment of cloud solutions with business objectives.

raw_data.title: Cloud Subject Matter Expert
raw_data.description: The Cloud SME provides expert guidance on cloud architecture, security, and best practices to optimize government IT systems. They evaluate cloud solutions, ensure compliance with federal regulations, and drive cloud adoption strategies. This role involves advising stakeholders, assessing risk, and implementing scalable, secure, and cost-effective cloud environments. The SME collaborates with engineering teams to design and deploy cloud-based solutions that meet mission-critical requirements. Strong expertise in AWS, Azure, or Google Cloud, along with FedRAMP, NIST, and FISMA compliance, is essential. They also provide technical leadership, conduct training, and stay updated on emerging cloud technologies.

raw_data.title: Cloud User Experience Specialist
raw_data.description: A Cloud User Experience (UX) Specialist is responsible for designing and optimizing the user experience for cloud-based applications and platforms. They collaborate with product managers, developers, and designers to create intuitive, efficient, and visually appealing interfaces that enhance the usability of cloud solutions. The Cloud UX Specialist conducts user research, usability testing, and feedback analysis to ensure that the cloud services meet user needs and expectations. They also work on designing user flows, wireframes, and prototypes, and ensure that accessibility and performance standards are integrated into the design process. Best practices include maintaining a user-centered design approach, applying design principles consistently, and working in close collaboration with development teams to ensure a seamless and responsive user experience.

raw_data.title: Cybersecurity Engineer
raw_data.description: The Cybersecurity Engineer is responsible for designing, implementing, and maintaining security solutions to protect an organization’s IT infrastructure. This includes securing networks, systems, and applications by applying tools such as firewalls, VPNs, IDS/IPS, and encryption. The engineer conducts vulnerability assessments, monitors for security incidents, and ensures compliance with industry standards and regulatory frameworks like NIST, FISMA, and FedRAMP. They also lead incident response efforts and provide security guidance to ensure the organization’s systems are protected against evolving cyber threats. The role requires expertise in network security, cloud security, and risk management.

raw_data.title: Cybersecurity Expert
raw_data.description: The Cybersecurity Expert is a senior-level professional with extensive knowledge and experience in protecting an organization’s IT infrastructure from cyber threats. This role involves designing and implementing robust security strategies, managing risk assessments, and ensuring compliance with cybersecurity regulations such as NIST, FISMA, FedRAMP, and other industry standards. The Cybersecurity Expert leads incident response efforts, conducts advanced threat hunting, and advises on security architecture and solutions. Additionally, they provide strategic guidance to senior leadership and ensure that security policies, practices, and technologies are continuously adapted to combat emerging threats. This role requires advanced expertise in network security, cloud security, penetration testing, and security governance.

raw_data.title: Cybersecurity SME
raw_data.description: The Cybersecurity Subject Matter Expert (SME) is a senior-level consultant with deep expertise in cybersecurity, providing strategic guidance and technical leadership across multiple security disciplines. The SME offers expert advice on security architecture, incident response, risk management, and compliance with standards such as NIST, FISMA, and FedRAMP. They lead the design and implementation of advanced security solutions, conduct risk assessments, and guide organizations in staying ahead of emerging threats. The SME also mentors junior staff and ensures that security strategies align with industry best practices and regulatory requirements. This role is essential for strengthening the organization's cybersecurity posture and responding to complex security challenges.

raw_data.title: Security Operations Center (SOC) Analyst I
raw_data.description: The SOC Analyst I is an entry-level cybersecurity professional responsible for monitoring and analyzing security threats within the Security Operations Center (SOC). This role involves detecting, investigating, and escalating security incidents while assisting in the overall protection of IT infrastructure. Working under the guidance of senior analysts, the SOC Analyst I helps respond to cyber threats, supports incident response efforts, and ensures compliance with federal cybersecurity frameworks such as NIST 800-53, FISMA, and FedRAMP. Ideal candidates will have a foundational understanding of network security, SIEM tools, and threat intelligence, with opportunities for career growth in cybersecurity operations.

raw_data.title: Security Operations Center (SOC) Analyst II
raw_data.description: The SOC Analyst II is a mid-level cybersecurity professional responsible for detecting, analyzing, and responding to security threats within the Security Operations Center (SOC). This role involves investigating security incidents, performing threat analysis, and enhancing security monitoring capabilities. The SOC Analyst II collaborates with senior analysts and incident response teams to mitigate risks and improve the organization's security posture. Candidates should have experience with SIEM tools, intrusion detection systems (IDS/IPS), threat intelligence, and forensic investigations, as well as a strong understanding of NIST 800-53, FISMA, and FedRAMP compliance requirements. This role offers opportunities for growth into senior cybersecurity positions.

raw_data.title: Security Operations Center (SOC) Analyst III
raw_data.description: The SOC Analyst III is a senior cybersecurity professional responsible for leading the detection, investigation, and response to complex security threats within the Security Operations Center (SOC). With extensive experience in SIEM tools, threat analysis, incident response, and vulnerability management, the SOC Analyst III plays a key role in protecting the organization’s systems and data. This position involves overseeing high-priority incidents, conducting advanced threat hunting, and mentoring junior analysts. The SOC Analyst III ensures compliance with federal cybersecurity standards such as NIST 800-53, FISMA, and FedRAMP while continuously improving security operations.

raw_data.title: Senior Information Cyber Security Engineer
raw_data.description: The Senior Information Systems Security Engineer is a highly experienced professional responsible for designing, implementing, and maintaining security solutions to protect the organization’s IT infrastructure and data. This role involves leading the development and application of security policies, frameworks, and controls, ensuring compliance with federal standards such as NIST 800-53, FISMA, and FedRAMP. The Senior Engineer will oversee vulnerability assessments, conduct penetration testing, and implement advanced security technologies such as firewalls, SIEM, IDS/IPS, and encryption. Additionally, they will collaborate with IT and development teams to integrate security into all stages of system development, monitoring, and operations. The ideal candidate will possess deep expertise in security architecture, incident response, and cloud security with a proven track record in risk mitigation and compliance assurance.

raw_data.title: Senior Information Systems Security Officer (ISSO)
raw_data.description: The Senior Information Cybersecurity Engineer is a highly experienced professional responsible for designing, implementing, and overseeing complex security solutions to protect an organization’s IT infrastructure. This role involves leading efforts in security architecture, incident response, and vulnerability management while ensuring compliance with regulatory frameworks such as NIST 800-53, FISMA, and FedRAMP. The Senior Engineer is responsible for developing advanced security measures, conducting risk assessments, and managing security incidents. This role also includes mentoring junior staff and ensuring security best practices are embedded throughout the organization’s operations and systems.
